{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"63b05eb4-6099-44fa-998e-c5e0a468e5c8","content":"On macOS, crash information is captured automatically by the OS:\n\n**Crash Reports** (always generated):\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\nLook for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your app name. You can also browse them in **Console.app → Crash Reports**.\n\n**Core Dumps** (disabled by default):\n```bash\n# Enable before running your app:\nulimit -c unlimited\nsudo sysctl kern.corefile=/cores/core.%P\n```\nCore files will appear in `/cores/`. Note that SIP may restrict this on some macOS versions.\n\nThe crash report (`.ips` file) is usually the fastest path — it includes the stack trace, signal info, and loaded libraries without any prior setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c7259466-7d15-40de-9166-64c318ea983a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports. Here's where to find them:\n\n1. **macOS Crash Reports**: Located in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (user-level) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (system-level).\n2. **Console.app**: You can also view them via the Console app under \"Crash Reports.\"\n\n\n3. **Core dumps**: macOS disables core dumps by default, but you can enable them by setting an unlimited core dump size before running the app — the dumps will then be written to `/cores/`.","outputTokens":400,"requestId":"9430:25127A:180D6F5:1B6361D:69E81F8E"},"id":"86329ad9-270d-4122-8655-b945b1e39289","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:08:40.101Z","parentId":"6b308d6b-dd39-41a1-bf23-11f84a224a90"}
